# Example AWS CLI profiles for soak testing (do not commit real secrets).
#
# Goal: use a profile such as `iota-soak` that is NOT your normal day-to-day
# profile (e.g. `iota-lab`), so destructive soak APIs never run as your main IAM user.
#
# --- Option A: IAM user `iota-soak` with access keys (simplest) ---
#
# 1. As a lab admin, create user iota-soak and AdministratorAccess (lab only).
# 2. aws configure --profile iota-soak
# 3. export AWS_PROFILE=iota-soak
#
# ~/.aws/config
# [profile iota-soak]
# region = us-east-1
# output = json
#
# ~/.aws/credentials
# [iota-soak]
# aws_access_key_id = AKIA...
# aws_secret_access_key = ...
#
# --- Option B: assume role into a soak role (no static keys for the soak principal) ---
#
# Create role `iota-soak-role` in the lab account with AdministratorAccess (lab only)
# and a trust policy allowing your normal user or SSO role to sts:AssumeRole.
#
# ~/.aws/config
# [profile iota-soak]
# role_arn = arn:aws:iam::YOUR_LAB_ACCOUNT_ID:role/iota-soak-role
# source_profile = iota-lab
# region = us-east-1
#
# Then: export AWS_PROFILE=iota-soak
#
# --- Option C: separate AWS Organization account ---
#
# Use a dedicated member account for soak; create iota-soak IAM user or SSO there,
# and point CloudTrail + iota integration at that account’s trail for pipeline tests.
